  <li><strong>Master the Color Spectrum for Quality Assessment</strong> - The hue of rosé wine directly indicates its production method and quality. Pale salmon-pink rosés (like Provence style) typically use the saignée method or direct press, offering delicate strawberry and citrus notes. Deeper coral or onion-skin tones often indicate longer skin contact or specific grape varieties like Grenache or Sangiovese. Avoid rosés with brown or orange tinges, which signal oxidation or poor winemaking.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precise 45-50°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike red wines, rosé's delicate aromatics and balanced acidity shine at this specific temperature range. Too cold (below 40°F) and you'll mute the fruit character; too warm (above 55°F) and the wine becomes flabby with diminished freshness. Use an ice bucket for 15-20 minutes or refrigerate for 2-3 hours to achieve this sweet spot.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting - Rosé Needs Immediate Enjoyment</strong> - Rosé wines are crafted for immediate consumption and gentle handling. Decanting can actually harm the wine by exposing it to excessive oxygen, which can fade the delicate color and mute the fresh fruit aromatics that define quality rosé. Pour directly from bottle to glass to preserve the wine's intended character.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Tulip-Shaped Glasses with Narrow Openings</strong> - The ideal rosé glass has a smaller bowl than red wine glasses but larger than white wine glasses - think Burgundy glass proportions. This shape concentrates the subtle aromatics while allowing proper aeration. Avoid wide-bowled glasses that dissipate the delicate floral and fruit notes that are rosé's hallmark.</li>

  <li><strong>Understand the 18-Month Freshness Window</strong> - Most rosés are designed to be consumed within 12-18 months of vintage date. The wine's primary fruit character and vibrant acidity deteriorate beyond this point. However, premium rosés from Bandol or serious Champagne rosés can develop complexity for 3-5 years. Check the vintage date and prioritize recent releases for optimal enjoyment.</li>

  <li><strong>Learn Provence vs. New World Style Differences</strong> - Provence rosés emphasize minerality, herbs de Provence, and restraint with 11-12.5% alcohol. New World styles (California, Australia) typically show riper fruit, higher alcohol (13-14%), and more pronounced sweetness. Understanding these regional philosophies helps you select rosés that match your preference and food pairing needs.</li>

