<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike red wines, most rosés are crafted for immediate enjoyment and don't benefit from extended cellaring. Understanding aging potential is crucial for maximizing your rosé experience.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Provence and light rosés</strong>: 1-2 years maximum. These delicate wines lose their signature freshness and bright acidity beyond this window</li>
<li><strong>Darker, structured rosés</strong> (Bandol, Tavel): 3-5 years. Higher phenolic content and residual tannins provide more aging backbone</li>
<li><strong>Sparkling rosé</strong>: 2-4 years for non-vintage, 5-8 years for premium vintage cuvées</li>
<li><strong>Rosé Champagne</strong>: 7-12 years, developing brioche and honeyed complexity</li>
</ul>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most rosés reach their peak within 6-18 months of release. The vibrant red berry flavors, crisp minerality, and zippy acidity that define quality rosé begin deteriorating after the second year. Exception: serious rosés from producers like Domaine Tempier (Bandol) develop tertiary notes of dried herbs and earth while maintaining structure.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Rosé aging typically brings color fading from salmon-pink to onion skin, fruit shifting from fresh strawberry to dried cherry, and acidity mellowing. Unlike reds, tannins are minimal and don't meaningfully evolve. Complexity rarely improves—instead, the wine loses its defining freshness.</p>

<h3>Storage Requirements</h3>
<p>Store rosé at consistent 55°F with 70% humidity. Unlike reds, position doesn't matter significantly for short-term storage. Keep away from light, which accelerates color degradation and creates off-flavors.</p>

<h3>Signs of Proper Development vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Proper aging: subtle color evolution, maintained balance. Spoilage signs: brown tints, oxidized aromas (sherry-like), flat acidity, or vinegar notes. If your rosé smells like wet cardboard or cooked vegetables, it's past its prime.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between dry and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosé contains less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter and showcases crisp, mineral-driven flavors like white peach and herbs. Sweet rosé, including White Zinfandel and some Moscato rosés, contains 12-45 grams of residual sugar, offering flavors of strawberry jam and tropical fruits. Most premium European rosés from Provence, Loire Valley, and Spain are crafted in the dry style, while many American rosés tend toward off-dry sweetness.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should rosé wine be served ice-cold or just chilled?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé should be served well-chilled at 45-50°F (7-10°C), not ice-cold which can mute its delicate aromatics and fruit flavors. Over-chilling masks the wine's complexity, while serving too warm emphasizes alcohol and reduces refreshment. Chill for 2-3 hours in the refrigerator or 20-30 minutes in an ice bucket, and let it warm slightly after pouring to reveal its full flavor profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long can I keep an opened bottle of rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">An opened bottle of rosé will maintain its quality for 3-5 days when properly stored in the refrigerator with a tight cork or wine stopper. The wine's bright acidity and lower tannin levels make it more susceptible to oxidation than reds but more stable than many light whites. Use a vacuum pump or inert gas system to extend freshness, and consume lighter, more delicate Provence-style rosés within 3 days, while fuller-bodied rosés from Bandol or Tavel can last up to 5 days.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine good for beginners who are new to wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, rosé is excellent for wine beginners because it bridges the gap between whites and reds with approachable fruit flavors and moderate acidity. The wine's food-friendly nature and lower tannin levels make it less intimidating than bold reds, while offering more complexity than many entry-level whites. Start with a dry Provence rosé or Spanish Garnacha rosé to experience classic styles, then explore sweeter versions if you prefer more residual sugar.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is assuming all rosé wines are sweet, leading people to avoid dry, sophisticated bottles from premium regions like Provence, Bandol, or Loire Valley. Many consumers also purchase rosé without checking the vintage, not realizing that most rosés are meant to be consumed within 1-2 years of release for optimal freshness. Additionally, judging quality solely by color intensity is misleading—pale salmon rosés from Provence can be more complex and expensive than darker pink wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can you age rosé wine like red wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most rosé wines are not designed for aging and should be consumed within 2-3 years of vintage for optimal freshness and fruit expression. However, exceptional rosés from regions like Bandol (made from Mourvèdre), Tavel, and some premium Champagne rosés can develop complexity over 5-10 years. These age-worthy rosés typically have higher acidity, more concentrated fruit, and sometimes brief skin contact that provides additional structure and tannins for longevity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best value rosé wine regions to explore?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Portugal's Vinho Verde rosé offers exceptional value with crisp, low-alcohol wines under $15, while Spain's Campo de Borja and Navarra produce excellent Garnacha-based rosés for $12-20. French alternatives to expensive Provence include Languedoc rosés and Loire Valley Cabernet d'Anjou, which provide similar quality at 30-50% less cost. For domestic options, Washington State and Oregon produce outstanding rosés that compete with French examples at more accessible price points.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do you tell if a rosé wine has gone bad?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Signs of spoiled rosé include a brownish or orange tint instead of fresh pink color, indicating oxidation, and flat or vinegary aromas replacing bright fruit scents. The wine may taste dull, overly acidic, or develop off-flavors like wet cardboard from cork taint or bacterial contamination. Fresh rosé should have vibrant color, clean aromatics of red berries or citrus, and crisp acidity—any deviation from these characteristics suggests the wine has deteriorated.</p>
